t be whole.\",\n  \"LLM Questions\": [\n    \"What is the primary goal of the problem, and what constraints do we have regarding the number of pieces?\",\n    \"If you have more c-shaped pieces than S-shaped pieces, how many S-shaped pieces do we make using these pieces, before making the Scc groups?\",\n    \"After having made a certain number of Scc groups, how do we determine the optimal way to use any remaining c-shaped pieces to maximize the number of Scc groups?\",\n    \"How does integer division affect your calculations of maximum numbers of groups?\",\n    \"How do the constraints of the problem influence our approach to optimizing the creation of Scc groups?\"\n  ],\n  \"Expected Answers to LLM Questions\": [\n    \"The primary goal is to maximize the number of 'Scc' groups, given N S-shaped pieces and M c-shaped pieces. The constraints are that 1 <= N, M <= 10^12.\",\n    \"If there are more c-shaped pieces than S-shaped pieces, we create S-shaped pieces from the c-shaped pieces. Make S-shaped pieces from c-shaped pieces to the number required to make the maximum possible Scc groups using current S-shaped pieces.\",\n    \"Any remaining c-shaped pieces are used to create additional S-shaped pieces by combining two c-shaped pieces into one S-shaped piece, using integer division, which may result in c-shaped pieces remaining.\",\n    \"Integer division ensures that we are dealing with whole groups only, because only whole numbers of pieces and groups can be made. Thus, all remainder groups are discarded.\",\n    \"The large upper bounds on N and M (10^12) mean we need to avoid solutions with excessive complexity, which are required to not time out. In this case the problem can be solved by a few calculations, so it is fine.\"\n  ]\n}\n```"